ansaction\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/db.ts`, lines 93-98\n\n`createDocument` performs two separate statements: `INSERT INTO documents` and `INSERT INTO versions`. If the first succeeds and the second fails (e.g., foreign key violation, though unlikely here), the document would exist without an initial version entry. This should be wrapped in a transaction.\n\nSimilarly, `updateDocumentContent` (lines 115-126) performs three operations (get, update, insert version) without a transaction. A failure midway could leave inconsistent state.\n\n### 8.5 No body size limit on document content via REST API\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/documents.ts`, lines 14-23\n\nA POST to `/documents` can include arbitrarily large `content` (up to Express's default 100kb JSON limit). Each document is stored in SQLite with no content length limit. Combined with the version history (which stores full content snapshots, not diffs), this can cause rapid storage growth.\n\n### 8.6 Version history stores full content snapshots, not deltas\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/db.ts`, line 123\n\nEvery version stores the full content string. For a document that undergoes many small edits, this means the `versions` table grows at O(n * document_size) where n is the number of edits. This is a significant storage inefficiency.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Severity Ratings\n\n| # | Issue | Severity |\n|---|-------|----------|\n| 1.1 | Double-close of WebSocketServer in stop() | HIGH |\n| 1.3 | Unbounded operation log memory leak | MEDIUM |\n| 5.1 | No input size limits on WebSocket messages | HIGH |\n| 5.2 | No authentication/authorization | HIGH |\n| 8.4 | Non-transactional multi-statement DB operations | MEDIUM |\n| 6.4 | No guard against calling start() twice | MEDIUM |\n| 1.4 | Session cleanup destroys operation log for reconnection | MEDIUM |\n| 6.2 | stop() does not handle errors from closeAll() | MEDIUM |\n| 4.1 | active_connections table is dead schema | LOW |\n| 4.2 | Operation interface is exported but unused | LOW |\n| 2.4 | baseVersion 0 accepted but produces confusing error | LOW |\n| 7.7 | No post-condition assertion in apply() | LOW |"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ab1ef2a (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 44227\ntool_uses: 11\nduration_ms: 147881</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4507f320-b808-4e74-bda1-a4565da48d2e","uuid":"90d29c2e-88f5-45dd-80df-fb5773aeaa74","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Do an adversarial code review of all source files in /workspace/src/ (db.ts, ot.ts, documents.ts, collaboration.ts, server.ts) and test files in /workspace/tests/ (ot.test.ts, api.test.ts, collaboration.test.ts).\n\nFocus on:\n1. **Bugs**: Race conditions, off-by-one errors, incorrect OT transform logic, memory leaks\n2. **Edge cases**: Empty documents, empty operations, simultaneous deletes of same range, operations on deleted content\n3. **Missing test coverage**: Any important scenarios not tested\n4. **Dead code**: Unused exports, unreachable branches\n5. **Security**: Potential crashes from malformed input, injection concerns\n6. **Server lifecycle**: Double-close issues, resource leaks, cleanup problems in stop()\n7. **OT correctness**: Does the transform function maintain the convergence property? Are there edge cases where two concurrent operations could produce inconsistent results?\n\nRead all the source files and test files, then provide a detailed report of any issues found. Do NOT make changes, just report findings.","agentId":"ab1ef2a","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have read all the files. Here is my detailed adversarial code review.\n\n---\n\n# Adversarial Code Review Report\n\n## 1. BUGS\n\n### 1.1 Double-close of WebSocketServer in `server.ts` stop() (HIGH)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/server.ts`, lines 57-75 and `/workspace/src/collaboration.ts`, lines 254-265\n\nThe `stop()` method in `server.ts` calls `collaboration.closeAll()` at line 57, which internally calls `this.wss.close()` at line 262 of `collaboration.ts`. Then `stop()` proceeds to call `wss.close()` again at line 60 of `server.ts`. This is a double-close on the same `WebSocketServer` instance. While `ws` library may tolerate this, it is a latent bug that can produce \"server not running\" errors or emit unexpected error events.\n\n```typescript\n// server.ts stop():\ncollaboration.closeAll();  // calls wss.close() internally\nif (wss) {\n  wss.close();  // double close!\n  wss = null;\n}\n```\n\nAdditionally, `collaboration.closeAll()` sets `this.wss = null` but the local variable `wss` in `server.ts` still holds the reference, so the second `.close()` call will definitely execute.\n\n### 1.2 Mutation of shared OpComponent objects in `normalize()` (HIGH)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/ot.ts`, lines 46-67\n\nThe `normalize` function uses spread syntax (`{ ...c }`) only when pushing a NEW component to the result array (line 63). When it merges adjacent same-type components, it mutates the existing `last` object in the `result` array. This is fine for `normalize` itself, but there is a subtler problem: the transform and compose functions call `normalize` on their output arrays, and those arrays contain freshly-created objects, so this is safe. However, the function signature and documentation imply it is a pure function on arbitrary input. If anyone ever calls `normalize` with components they intend to reuse, the mutation of `last` would cause silent data corruption. This is a design hazard, not currently triggered but fragile.\n\n### 1.3 Operation log grows unboundedly -- memory leak (MEDIUM)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/collaboration.ts`, lines 34-43 and line 204\n\nEach `DocumentSession` has an `operationLog: Map<number, OpComponent[]>` that grows with every operation and is never pruned. For a long-lived session with many edits, this will consume increasing memory without bound. The log is only cleared when the session is destroyed (all clients disconnect), but during active collaboration it grows indefinitely.\n\n### 1.4 Session cleanup destroys operation log needed for reconnection (MEDIUM)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/collaboration.ts`, lines 232-241\n\nWhen the last client disconnects (line 237-238), the session -- including its `operationLog` -- is deleted. When a new client connects and creates a fresh session, the new session starts with an empty `operationLog`. If a client had received sync at version N and then the session was recycled, and that client reconnects and sends an operation based on version N, the server will try to look up operations from version N+1 onwards in the new session's empty log and fail with \"Missing operation for version V in log\". This makes the system fragile around reconnection after brief total disconnection.\n\n### 1.5 Race condition: concurrent WebSocket messages on the same session (MEDIUM)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/collaboration.ts`, lines 132-229\n\nThe `handleMessage` method is not guarded by any form of mutual exclusion. While Node.js is single-threaded, the method performs async-like work: it modifies `session.content`, `session.version`, and calls `this.store.updateDocumentContent` (a synchronous SQLite call, so this is actually safe in practice). However, if `better-sqlite3` were ever replaced with an async DB driver, or if any async operation were inserted into this path, concurrent messages from different clients could interleave and produce inconsistent state. The design does not make this safety constraint explicit.\n\n### 1.6 `clientCounter` never resets -- not a bug but a monotonicity concern (LOW)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/collaboration.ts`, line 49\n\nThe `clientCounter` is a simple incrementing number. Across a very long-lived server, it could theoretically overflow `Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER` (9007199254740991), though in practice this is unreachable. No real bug, but noted.\n\n---\n\n## 2. EDGE CASES\n\n### 2.1 Empty operations (retain(0), delete(0), insert(\"\")) are accepted but wasteful\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/ot.ts`, lines 298-336\n\nThe `validateOperation` function permits `retain(0)`, `delete(0)`, and `insert(\"\")` as valid components. These are semantically no-ops but will cause unnecessary version increments, database writes, and broadcasts. The `normalize` function strips them when composing or transforming, but a client can submit an operation consisting entirely of no-ops, and it will still trigger a version bump and DB persistence.\n\n### 2.2 Submitting an operation against an empty document with retain/delete components\n\nAn operation like `[{type: \"retain\", count: 0}]` against an empty document will pass validation and the input-length check (0 === 0) and produce no change. But an operation like `[{type: \"delete\", count: 1}]` against an empty document will correctly fail with an input length mismatch. This is handled correctly.\n\n### 2.3 Simultaneous deletes of the same range\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/ot.ts`, lines 181-185\n\nWhen both `a` and `b` delete the same characters (the `delete-vs-delete` case), the transform correctly cancels them out (no output for either prime). This is correct OT behavior. However, one scenario is not tested: what happens when one client deletes a range and another client inserts within that range? The transform function will correctly transform the insert to appear adjacent to the deletion boundary, but the intent of the inserter (to insert inside specific text) is semantically lost. This is an inherent OT limitation, not a bug, but it is a known user-experience issue.\n\n### 2.4 `baseVersion` of 0 is accepted\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/collaboration.ts`, lines 145-148\n\nA `baseVersion` of 0 passes validation (`>= 0`), but the initial version of a document is 1. If a client sends `baseVersion: 0`, the loop on line 164 iterates `for (let v = 1; v <= session.version; v++)` and tries to look up `session.operationLog.get(1)`. For a freshly created session, the operationLog is empty, so this will fail with \"Missing operation for version 1 in log\". The error is caught and reported, but it is a confusing error message for what is really an invalid baseVersion. The validation should reject `baseVersion < 1` or `baseVersion < session's initial version`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. MISSING TEST COVERAGE\n\n### 3.1 No test for `compose` correctness with delete-then-insert\n\nThe `compose` tests only cover two cases: two insertions, and insert-then-delete. Missing scenarios:\n- Compose of two deletions\n- Compose of delete-then-insert\n- Compose of operations on an empty document\n- Compose identity (retain-only) with another operation\n\n### 3.2 No test for `transform` with two clients both deleting the exact same range\n\nThe overlap test (`transform two overlapping deletes`) uses partially overlapping ranges. A test where both clients delete exactly the same range (e.g., both delete chars 2-4 of \"hello world\") is missing.\n\n### 3.3 No test for operations on an empty document via WebSocket\n\nThe test `should handle rapid sequential operations from one client` starts with an empty document, but only sends inserts. There is no test for what happens when a client sends an operation with `baseVersion: 1` against an empty document with only retain(0) or an empty components array.\n\n### 3.4 No test for `updateDocumentContent` creating correct version numbering\n\nThe `db.ts` `updateDocumentContent` method calculates `nextVersion` from the latest version. No test verifies that calling `updateDocumentContent` multiple times produces monotonically increasing version numbers without gaps.\n\n### 3.5 No test for server `start()` being called twice\n\nWhat happens if `start()` is called twice on the same `AppInstance`? It creates a new `httpServer` and `wss` each time, orphaning the previous ones. This is a resource leak with no test or guard.\n\n### 3.6 No test for `closeAll()` with active clients\n\nWhile `afterEach` closes clients and calls `stop()`, there is no test that verifies clients receive a close frame or that in-flight operations are handled gracefully during shutdown.\n\n### 3.7 No test for `normalize` with mixed adjacent types\n\ne.g., `[retain(3), delete(2), delete(3)]` should merge the deletes into `delete(5)`. Tests only cover adjacent same-type merging for retains and inserts, not deletes.\n\n### 3.8 No test for extremely large operations\n\nNo test exercises behavior with very large documents or operations (e.g., retain(1000000)), which could expose performance issues or integer overflow edge cases.\n\n### 3.9 No test for the `PUT /documents/:id` endpoint missing content field\n\nThe test checks for missing title but does not verify that sending `{ title: \"X\" }` without content returns 400.\n\n### 3.10 No test for WebSocket reconnection to the same document\n\nThe `should persist changes across sessions` test reconnects, but does not verify that the new session's version number is correct and that the client can send operations against the new version.\n\n---\n\n## 4. DEAD CODE\n\n### 4.1 `active_connections` table is never used\n\n**File:** `/workspace/schema.sql`, lines 19-23\n\nThe `active_connections` table is defined in the schema but is never read from or written to in any source file. The `CollaborationManager` tracks connections entirely in memory via `session.clients`. This table is completely dead schema.\n\n### 4.2 `Operation` interface is exported but never used\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/ot.ts`, lines 18-23\n\nThe `Operation` interface (with `baseVersion` and `components`) is exported but never imported or used by any other file. The `collaboration.ts` defines its own `ClientMessage` interface instead.\n\n### 4.3 `outputLength` is exported but never used outside tests\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/ot.ts`, lines 36-43\n\nThe `outputLength` function is exported and only used in `ot.test.ts`. No production code calls it. It may be intended for future use, but currently it is dead production code.\n\n---\n\n## 5. SECURITY\n\n### 5.1 No input size limits on WebSocket messages (HIGH)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/collaboration.ts`, lines 114-121\n\nThere is no limit on the size of incoming WebSocket messages. A malicious client could send an operation with millions of components, or a single `insert` component with a multi-gigabyte text string, causing the server to exhaust memory during JSON parsing, transformation, or application.\n\n### 5.2 No authentication or authorization (HIGH)\n\nAny client can connect to any document's WebSocket endpoint and modify it. There is no authentication mechanism. While this may be intentional for a demo, it is a significant security concern for any deployment.\n\n### 5.3 No rate limiting on WebSocket operations (MEDIUM)\n\nA client can send operations at an unlimited rate, potentially overwhelming the server. Combined with 5.1, this enables a trivial denial-of-service attack.\n\n### 5.4 Document ID in URL is not validated for format (LOW)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/collaboration.ts`, line 67\n\nThe regex `/\\/ws\\/documents\\/([^/?]+)/` accepts any non-slash, non-question-mark string as a document ID. While the code checks that the document exists, it still executes a database query for arbitrary strings, which could be very long. There is no length limit on the document ID path parameter.\n\n### 5.5 No Content-Length limit on REST API (MEDIUM)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/server.ts`, line 20\n\nThe `express.json()` middleware is used without a `limit` option. The default limit is 100kb, which is set by Express. This is reasonable but worth noting -- for documents that could be very large, this may be insufficient; or if raised, it becomes an attack vector.\n\n### 5.6 `validateOperation` allows negative zero (VERY LOW)\n\nThe check `comp.count < 0` does not catch `-0` (negative zero in JavaScript is not `< 0`). This is harmless since `-0 === 0` in all arithmetic, but is a theoretical imprecision.\n\n### 5.7 SQL Injection is mitigated by prepared statements (GOOD)\n\nThe `DocumentStore` correctly uses prepared statements throughout. No SQL injection risk found.\n\n---\n\n## 6. SERVER LIFECYCLE\n\n### 6.1 Double-close of WebSocketServer (reiteration of 1.1)\n\nAs described in section 1.1, `stop()` causes a double-close of the `WebSocketServer`. This is the most significant lifecycle issue.\n\n### 6.2 `stop()` does not handle errors from `collaboration.closeAll()`\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/server.ts`, line 57\n\nIf `collaboration.closeAll()` throws (e.g., due to a WebSocket error during close), the rest of `stop()` -- including closing the HTTP server and the database -- will not execute. This leaves resources leaked. The call should be wrapped in a try-catch.\n\n### 6.3 `store.close()` after `httpServer.close()` can fail if pending requests access the DB\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/server.ts`, lines 64-74\n\nThe HTTP server is closed with `httpServer.close()`, which stops accepting new connections but waits for existing connections to finish. However, `store.close()` is called immediately after the close callback, meaning any in-flight request that was already being processed could attempt to access a closed database. In practice, since `better-sqlite3` is synchronous and Node.js is single-threaded, this is unlikely to manifest, but the ordering is not formally safe.\n\n### 6.4 No guard against calling `start()` twice\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/server.ts`, lines 36-53\n\nIf `start()` is called twice, it creates a new `httpServer` and `wss`, orphaning the previous ones without closing them. This results in leaked sockets and a leaked port binding. There is no check like `if (httpServer) throw new Error('already started')`.\n\n### 6.5 `stop()` does not reset `collaboration.closeAll()` gracefully if `stop()` called without `start()`\n\nIf `stop()` is called before `start()`, `collaboration.closeAll()` runs on a CollaborationManager that was never set up with a WebSocketServer (`this.wss` is null), which is handled (the null check on line 261). Then `wss` is null (line 59) and `httpServer` is null (line 64), so those blocks are skipped. But `store.close()` IS called on a DB that may still be open from `createApp()`. This means calling `stop()` without `start()` will close the DB, and a subsequent `start()` would then fail because the DB is closed. The API tests (`api.test.ts`) call `stop()` without `start()` which works only because `createApp()` creates a fresh in-memory DB and `stop()` closes it cleanly.\n\n---\n\n## 7. OT CORRECTNESS\n\n### 7.1 Convergence property: analysis\n\nThe `transform` function implements the standard OT algorithm. Let me verify the key convergence property: `apply(apply(doc, a), bPrime) === apply(apply(doc, b), aPrime)`.\n\n**Insert vs Insert:** Left wins (a's insert goes first). The transform produces:\n- `aPrime`: a's insert stays, plus a retain over b's insert\n- `bPrime`: b's insert stays, plus a retain over a's insert\n\nThis is correct and consistent with the standard \"left-wins\" tie-breaking.\n\n**Delete vs Delete (overlapping):** The overlapping portion cancels out. The non-overlapping portions of each delete remain in the respective prime operations. This is correct.\n\n**Insert vs Delete:** An insert by `a` at a position within `b`'s delete range: After transform, `a`'s insert will appear at the boundary of the deletion. The insert is preserved even though the surrounding text is deleted. This is standard OT behavior and is correct.\n\n**Retain vs Retain:** Both operations retain the same characters. Correct.\n\n### 7.2 Potential issue: transform does not handle empty component arrays\n\nIf both `aComponents` and `bComponents` are empty arrays (`[]`), the while loop on line 149 never executes, and the function returns `[[], []]` (after normalization). This is correct for an empty document.\n\nIf one is empty and the other is not, the loop will run: the non-empty side will produce components while the other side produces nulls. For insert-type components this is fine (they don't consume input). For retain/delete components, `a` or `b` will be null at line 170, triggering a throw. This is correct behavior -- if the input lengths don't match, the transform should throw.\n\n### 7.3 Potential issue: transform with operations that have different input lengths\n\nThe transform function assumes both `a` and `b` operate on the same document (same input length). If they don't, the function will throw \"Operation length mismatch during transform\" at line 171. This is correct -- the caller (`handleMessage`) should ensure both operations are against documents of the same length.\n\n### 7.4 OT transform correctness for three-way concurrent edits\n\nThe server processes operations serially and transforms each incoming operation against all operations since its base version. This is the standard \"server-side OT\" approach and is correct for convergence, assuming the transform function satisfies the TP1 property (which the standard algorithm does). However, it does NOT satisfy TP2 (the three-way transform property), which means a peer-to-peer OT system would not converge. Since this is a centralized server architecture, TP1 is sufficient and the approach is correct.\n\n### 7.5 Operations stored in the log are the TRANSFORMED versions\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/collaboration.ts`, line 204\n\nThe operation stored in `session.operationLog.set(session.version, components)` is the already-transformed version (after transforming against all intervening operations). This is correct: future incoming operations need to be transformed against the server's canonical operation sequence, not the client's original operations.\n\n### 7.6 Edge case: operation with retain count exceeding remaining document length\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/ot.ts`, lines 70-97\n\nThe `apply` function checks that the total `inputLength` matches the document length, but it does not check that individual `pos + c.count` accesses stay within bounds during application. If a malformed operation has `[retain(3), retain(3)]` on a 6-character document, it works fine. But if normalization produces `[retain(6)]`, it also works fine. The `slice` operation will handle out-of-bounds gracefully in JavaScript (returning fewer characters), but the `inputLength` pre-check prevents this from being an issue. The defense is correct.\n\n### 7.7 The `apply` function does not verify pos === doc.length at the end\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/ot.ts`, line 96\n\nAfter processing all components, `pos` should equal `doc.length`. The pre-check of `inputLength` guarantees this mathematically (retain and delete advance pos by exactly their count, and insert doesn't advance pos). But there is no post-condition assertion. If a bug were introduced in `inputLength` or `apply`, the mismatch would go undetected. A paranoid implementation would assert `pos === doc.length` at the end.\n\n---\n\n## 8. ADDITIONAL FINDINGS\n\n### 8.1 `connectWs` test helper has a subtle race in `firstMessage` promise\n\n**File:** `/workspace/tests/collaboration.test.ts`, lines 37-72\n\nThe `firstMessage` promise constructor checks `messageQueue.length > 0` synchronously on line 58. But the message listener (line 45) pushes to `messageQueue` only if `messageWaiter` is null. The `firstMessage` promise sets `messageWaiter` on line 62 only if the queue is empty. There is a TOCTOU race: between checking `messageQueue.length` on line 58 and setting `messageWaiter` on line 62, a message could arrive and be pushed to `messageQueue` (since `messageWaiter` is still null). This message would be in the queue but the `firstMessage` promise would hang waiting via `messageWaiter`. In practice, this is nearly impossible in a test environment since the WebSocket hasn't connected yet (the `open` event resolves the outer promise, and messages arrive after `open`), but it is a structural defect.\n\n### 8.2 `waitForMessage` vs `waitForMessageOfType` -- message swallowing\n\n**File:** `/workspace/tests/collaboration.test.ts`, lines 74-97\n\n`waitForMessage` uses `ws.once('message', ...)` which registers a one-time listener. If `waitForMessage` and `waitForMessageOfType` are both active on the same WebSocket (which happens in some tests), they will compete for messages. The `waitForMessageOfType` registers a persistent listener that only resolves when the right type arrives, but `waitForMessage` will consume the first message regardless of type. If the first message is not the expected type for `waitForMessage`, the test may pass incorrectly or the `waitForMessageOfType` listener will miss a message. This works in the current tests because the ordering is carefully controlled, but it is fragile.\n\n### 8.3 `handleDisconnect` can be called twice (harmless but untidy)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/collaboration.ts`, lines 127-129\n\nBoth `ws.on('close')` and `ws.on('error')` call `handleDisconnect`. If an error causes the WebSocket to close, both events fire, calling `handleDisconnect` twice for the same client. The second call is harmless (it deletes a non-existent key from the Map), but it may cause the session to be double-checked for emptiness and double-deleted from `this.sessions` (also harmless since `Map.delete` on a missing key is a no-op). No actual bug, but worth noting.\n\n### 8.4 The `createDocument` method does not use a transaction\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/db.ts`, lines 93-98\n\n`createDocument` performs two separate statements: `INSERT INTO documents` and `INSERT INTO versions`. If the first succeeds and the second fails (e.g., foreign key violation, though unlikely here), the document would exist without an initial version entry. This should be wrapped in a transaction.\n\nSimilarly, `updateDocumentContent` (lines 115-126) performs three operations (get, update, insert version) without a transaction. A failure midway could leave inconsistent state.\n\n### 8.5 No body size limit on document content via REST API\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/documents.ts`, lines 14-23\n\nA POST to `/documents` can include arbitrarily large `content` (up to Express's default 100kb JSON limit). Each document is stored in SQLite with no content length limit. Combined with the version history (which stores full content snapshots, not diffs), this can cause rapid storage growth.\n\n### 8.6 Version history stores full content snapshots, not deltas\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/db.ts`, line 123\n\nEvery version stores the full content string. For a document that undergoes many small edits, this means the `versions` table grows at O(n * document_size) where n is the number of edits. This is a significant storage inefficiency.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Severity Ratings\n\n| # | Issue | Severity |\n|---|-------|----------|\n| 1.1 | Double-close of WebSocketServer in stop() | HIGH |\n| 1.3 | Unbounded operation log memory leak | MEDIUM |\n| 5.1 | No input size limits on WebSocket messages | HIGH |\n| 5.2 | No authentication/authorization | HIGH |\n| 8.4 | Non-transactional multi-statement DB operations | MEDIUM |\n| 6.4 | No guard against calling start() twice | MEDIUM |\n| 1.4 | Session cleanup destroys operation log for reconnection | MEDIUM |\n| 6.2 | stop() does not handle errors from closeAll() | MEDIUM |\n| 4.1 | active_connections table is dead schema | LOW |\n| 4.2 | Operation interface is exported but unused | LOW |\n| 2.4 | baseVersion 0 accepted but produces confusing error | LOW |\n| 7.7 | No post-condition assertion in apply() | LOW |"}],"totalDurationMs":147881,"totalTokens":44227,"totalToolUseCount":11,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2206,"cache_read_input_tokens":35964,"output_tokens":6056,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2206,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[]}}}
